# Kubernetes + HAProxy Architecture (NodePort Setup)

## 🔷 Overall Flow

User → HAProxy (Public EC2) → NodeIP:NodePort → Kubernetes Service → Pods → MongoDB

---

## 🔷 Step-by-Step Flow

1. User Request

   * User accesses application using:
     http://<HAProxy-Public-IP>

2. HAProxy (External Load Balancer)

   * Listens on port 80
   * Forwards traffic to Kubernetes nodes
   * Uses round-robin load balancing

3. NodePort (Cluster Entry Point)

   * Example: 10.0.1.x:31000
   * Open on all worker nodes
   * Receives traffic from HAProxy

4. kube-proxy (Internal Routing)

   * Intercepts NodePort traffic
   * Routes request to the correct service

5. Kubernetes Service (photo-service)

   * Type: NodePort
   * Acts as internal load balancer
   * Distributes traffic across pods

6. Pods (Application Layer)

   * Running photo-app containers
   * Listening on port 3000
   * Processes incoming requests

7. Database Access (MongoDB)

   * Accessed via: mongo-service
   * Internal DNS resolution
   * Connection string: mongodb://mongo-service:27017

8. Response Flow
   MongoDB → Pod → Service → NodePort → HAProxy → User

---

## 🔷 Components Responsibility

* HAProxy
  External load balancer (public access)

* NodePort
  Entry point into Kubernetes cluster

* kube-proxy
  Handles internal routing

* Service
  Load balances traffic between pods

* Pods
  Runs application logic

* Mongo Service
  Provides database access

---

## 🔷 Important Concepts

* Double Load Balancing

  1. HAProxy → Nodes
  2. Service → Pods

* Service Discovery

  * mongo-service automatically resolves via Kubernetes DNS

* Scalability

  * Pods can scale without changing external access

---

## 🔷 HAProxy Sample Config

frontend http_front
bind *:80
default_backend k8s_nodes

backend k8s_nodes
balance roundrobin
server node1 10.0.1.146:31000 check
server node2 10.0.1.61:31000 check
server node3 10.0.1.215:31000 check

---

## 🔷 Final Summary

HAProxy handles external traffic → NodePort exposes service → Service routes to pods → Pods process request → MongoDB responds


